            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-06-07T21:51:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-01-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="174" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d174">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On June 10, 1952, Senator <persName>Richard B. Russell</persName>, Chairman of
                    the Armed Services Committee, suggested to President <persName corresp="#p_THS1"
                        >Truman</persName> that a military commission of neutral nations be asked to
                    observe treatment of prisoners held by the United Nations in Korea. The
                    President thought the idea had merit and asked the Secretary of Defense to
                    implement the plan. When Secretary <persName corresp="#p_ADG1"
                        >Acheson</persName> learned of the decision over the radio, he immediately
                    warned <persName corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName> that the invitations to the
                    suggested neutral nations—Sweden, Switzerland, India, Pakistan, and
                    Indonesia—would be declined. (See the memorandum by <persName corresp="#p_AJM1"
                        >Allison</persName>, <ref target="#pg_405">page 405</ref>.) <persName
                        corresp="#p_ADG1">Acheson</persName>’s appraisal was right and the scheme
                    came to nothing. Secretary <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">Acheson</persName> later
                    wrote that the President’s approval of Russell’s plan was “one of the very few
                    instances when the President did not consult me on a matter of foreign policy.”
                    See <hi rend="italic">Present at the Creation</hi>, page 655, for <persName
                        corresp="#p_ADG1">Acheson</persName>’s comments and <hi rend="italic">Public
                        Papers of the Presidents of the United States: <persName corresp="#p_THS1"
                            >Harry S. Truman</persName>, 1952–1953</hi>, pages 414–415, for
                        <persName>Russell</persName>’s letter to <persName corresp="#p_THS1"
                        >Truman</persName> and the President’s memorandum to the Secretary of
                    Defense.</p>
            </div>
